</p>

<h5><em><u>January 6, 2004</u><br />
New Hampshire</em></h5>

<p>I&rsquo;m heading for the nationwide College Convention in Manchester, New Hampshire, to get a handle on the youth vote. I took a couple of weeks off for the holidays, and it seems I didn&rsquo;t miss much. Kerry continued his negative campaigning, which at this point is about all he&rsquo;s known for. Ask somebody on the street if Kerry is for or against the war in Iraq. Same with Edwards. The <em>Times </em>ran an article today on how Kerry and Edwards are competing for third and fourth in Iowa. Do they not hear the bells tolling?</p>

<p>The big news recently is Wesley Clark&rsquo;s refusal to run for vice president. There are times when I think a Dean/Clark ticket is the only thing standing between us and school prayer, private prisons, and mad cow on the lunch menu. And I&rsquo;ve been worried recently that, with the current deficit spending, there won&rsquo;t be any Social Security or Medicare when I&rsquo;m old. I was kind of looking forward to a subsidized retirement in the old folks&rsquo; home, wearing my white nightgown and flannel slippers and playing bridge all day.</p>

<p>What&rsquo;s clear is that this race has boiled down to two men, Wesley Clark and Howard Dean. The Democratic machine is likely to come out for Clark. The real question is: How long will the other anti-Dean candidates hang on by their fingernails, siphoning support from the general?</p>

<p>I plan to spend the next four days figuring out what the youth vote has to say about all this. Perhaps I can bankrupt a couple of young Republicans at the card table while I&rsquo;m at it, so they can feel what I felt when I was their age.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Call Daddy,&rdquo; I&rsquo;ll tell them as I clean out their trust funds. &ldquo;Tell him to FedEx your bootstraps.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Prediction: Dean takes first in Iowa by more than anyone expects. Kerry comes in a distant third and calls it a victory. John Edwards places a sick fourth.</p>

<h5><u><em>January 8</em></u></h5>

<p>There are days now when I take speed for no good reason at all, just because I miss my girlfriend or to kill some time. The hotel-room door is bolted shut. I open it only when the bellboy comes by with another packet of Folgers for the four-cup coffeemaker. Sometimes it&rsquo;s hard to get out of bed because of the jet lag.</p>

<p>The College Convention 2004 is on the first floor of the hotel. Kucinich electrified the crowd today. When asked about <span class="smallcaps">NAFTA</span> and the <span class="smallcaps">WTO</span>, he said he would pull out of both. He said he would work to rid the world of nuclear weapons, and the kids cheered. I felt bad for not cheering. I wanted to cheer for the idea of a world without nuclear weapons, but I think that would require a lot of trust. Anytime you say to someone, &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll show you mine if you show me yours,&rdquo; you could end up being the only one naked.</p>

<p>I hung out with Kucinich for a few minutes before the event. He gave me a hug. His security guard asked if there was anyone in the crowd I thought he should worry about, and I told him to watch out for Richard Bosa, a fringe Republican candidate. Bosa&rsquo;s a large man who wears cowboy boots and a trench coat. Somehow he reminds me of my father, which might be why I felt he was a threat.</p>

<p>Bosa was there to take part in a forum called &ldquo;They Also Ran&rdquo; with other fringe candidates. I believe there&rsquo;s something very wrong with anyone who wants to be president, and the truly minor candidates, the ones who have never held any kind of office and have no supporters, prove my point best. They&rsquo;re the image of the political beast within, stripped of any window dressing or message.</p>

<p>John Buchanan, a fringe candidate from Miami, claimed the Bush administration knew what was coming on 9/11. He also assured the crowd that he was the only candidate who would admit to getting high every single day. (This got major applause.) &ldquo;After what happened on 9/11,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;you have to.&rdquo;</p>

<h5><u><em>January 9</em></u></h5>

<p>In the morning I slept through Carol Moseley Braun&rsquo;s speech but made it downstairs in time to catch Kerry&rsquo;s act. He had twenty campaign workers lined up at the entrance to the hall screaming, &ldquo;Go, Kerry, Go!&rdquo; The candidate came down from the dressing room, plowed through his supporters, and went straight to the bathroom. Three guards were immediately posted outside the bathroom so that nobody could disturb the senator. Meanwhile his supporters continued chanting at the top of their lungs, &ldquo;Go, Kerry, Go!&rdquo; If that ever happened to me, I would really freeze up.</p>

<p>Kerry didn&rsquo;t say much new. He gave vague answers to questions from the audience. Pressed for his position on marijuana (as were all the other candidates), he responded that he&rsquo;s waiting for the results of a new study. The crowd booed.</p>

<h5><em><u>January 12</u><br />
Iowa</em></h5>

<p>A week and a day before Iowans will meet in precinct caucuses to select delegates for the party conventions, I meet Josh Bearman at the Eastern Iowa Airport. Josh is writing a piece for the <em>Believer </em>magazine, and we&rsquo;ve agreed to split expenses. We rent a red Grand Am with a <span class="smallcaps">CD</span> player. The guy behind the counter asks if we would like to upgrade to a Saturn <span class="smallcaps">SUV</span> for five dollars more a day. I tell him no. I read a <em>New Yorker</em> article that said people drive<span class="smallcaps"> SUV</span>s because they make you feel safe, and nothing is more dangerous than feeling safe.</p>

<p>There&rsquo;s a Perfect Storm brewing. That&rsquo;s the name for the wave of out-of-state Dean supporters arriving this week. They&rsquo;re coming to get out the vote on Monday and make sure every Iowa resident committed to Dean makes his or her caucus. The other candidates have supporters arriving, too, but not in such large numbers.</p>

<p>Josh and I are staying for a couple of days at a house near the University of Iowa. Today David Redlawsk, a political-science professor and Democratic county chair, invited us to talk to a class he&rsquo;s teaching over winter break. We were supposed to discuss what it means to be a political journalist, something I know nothing about.</p>

<p>&ldquo;What if everybody wrote like you?&rdquo; one of David&rsquo;s students asked us.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know if that would be a good thing,&rdquo; I told him.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I usually write about video games,&rdquo; Josh said.</p>

<p>One young woman said she was working for Kerry. &ldquo;What do you think?&rdquo; I asked her.</p>

<p>&ldquo;We&rsquo;re not allowed to talk to the press,&rdquo; she replied.</p>

<p>&ldquo;You should fail her,&rdquo; I told David later in his office. &ldquo;That&rsquo;s the problem with those campaigns, their top-down management style. You should write it on her transcript: &lsquo;Any press is better than no press.&rsquo; &rdquo;</p>

<p>David laughed but didn&rsquo;t agree.</p>

<h5><u><em>January 14</em></u></h5>

<p>Here&rsquo;s what it&rsquo;s like covering the campaign on a shoestring: Sometimes, when you&rsquo;re staying at the home of someone you&rsquo;ve never met and there&rsquo;s only whole-bean coffee and no grinder, you have to improvise. You start by boiling the beans in a pot, but it takes an hour, and the coffee comes out light and creamy-looking and slightly sour. It&rsquo;s almost noon, so you slice the wet beans into thirds, careful not to slit your fingertips, and put them back in the pot. The beans are slippery, though, and some shoot from your grasp and roll beneath the refrigerator. After another twenty minutes of boiling, you fish out the pieces and spoon them into a filter, which you place in the coffeemaker. Then you pour the brown water over the mush. You spill a lot and end up with only half a cup and a mess to clean. Your host will be home tomorrow. Luckily you&rsquo;ll be long gone by then.</p>

<p>Once you&rsquo;ve had some caffeine, you start to think a little clearer. You miss your girlfriend. (She sent you a picture yesterday from some party she went to. In the picture she&rsquo;s wearing a latex bikini over a body stocking. In the background is a man in leather chaps; his ass is showing.) The campaigns won&rsquo;t let you back on the bus because the bus is full. It was easy to get on before, but that was then. This is the big time, buddy, and you and whatever third-rate organization you work for aren&rsquo;t worth the time of day.</p>

<p>Last night you were drinking with a woman from Iowans for Clark, a former actress who moved to Iowa to pursue a degree in creative nonfiction. She&rsquo;s a vegan and has a triangular face. You tell her that vegan babies die easily; children need milk. She loves Wesley Clark because he looks great in a Speedo and &ldquo;he&rsquo;s the only one who can beat Bush.&rdquo; (Every candidate, it seems, is the only one who can beat Bush.) She doesn&rsquo;t like Dean, but she&rsquo;s not sure why. Before your ride left, you asked if she was going your way, and she said she was, but you didn&rsquo;t know she meant walking. So you walked to Muscatine at three in the morning and nearly froze.</p>

<p class="ckeditor-shortcode"><figure class="photo photo-outset-center-small">
	<div>
					<div>
				<img src="data:image/svg+xml;charset=utf-8,%3Csvg xmlns%3D'http%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2F2000%2Fsvg' viewBox%3D'0 0 1560 2364'%2F%3E"
