																	</div>
																								</figcaption>
							</div>
			</div>
</figure>
</p>

<h5><em><u>January 19</u><br />
Iowa caucus day</em></h5>

<p>Less than a third of the people who will vote in the general election are expected to caucus today. The streets of Des Moines are nervous. The experts are all declining to speculate. The major newspapers are suddenly saying, &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t look to us,&rdquo; as if encouraging people to come to their own conclusions. Joe Trippi is telling people Dean may come in fourth with 18 percent. The only person sure to win is John Edwards, because no matter how well he does, it will be better than anybody thought.</p>

<p>Edwards has ratcheted his message so tight that he sounds like a Baptist preacher at a revival meeting. At the rallies yesterday, people hollered when he proclaimed he would &ldquo;cut the lobbyists off at the knees.&rdquo; Two women fainted. Hundreds waited in the room next door, and anybody who walked in undecided walked out rooting for Edwards.</p>

<p>Kerry&rsquo;s rally was just the opposite. It went on too long, and people left before the senator even took the microphone. There were twenty to thirty politicos onstage with him, as well as his wife and children, and the emcee sounded like a wrestling announcer: &ldquo;And now, your Polk County Democratic leadership.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&rdquo; Gary Hart and Ted Kennedy were up there. It was the big Democratic machine leaving its wheel prints across the rich Iowa soil. I felt guilty for eating one of the corn dogs in the press area. If I&rsquo;m not going to say something nice about a campaign, I feel that I shouldn&rsquo;t eat their food.</p>

<p>This morning my e-mail inbox was filled with hate mail because I called journalist Matt Drudge a &ldquo;scumbag&rdquo; in the <em>San Francisco Chronicle</em>. I guess you shouldn&rsquo;t pick a fight if you&rsquo;re not willing to see it through. Drudge put my article up on his website, and now I&rsquo;m getting e-mails from his supporters in the conservative press telling me what a dumb liberal I am. These strong-arm tactics really work. I saw it happen when I was in Israel: you can have ten people waving peace signs, but it only takes one guy swinging his fists to break the whole thing up. That&rsquo;s why the Right so often wins: they&rsquo;re street fighters.</p>

<p>The best moment of the night was Chuck Berry performing for Richard Gephardt&rsquo;s rally. It was all union members, and the beer was flowing. Outside the hotel, Teamster trucks circled like buzzards around a dying calf.</p>

<p>The audience at the Gephardt event looked just like the people I grew up around in Chicago. When I was eighteen, I got kicked out of the group home where I lived, and I moved in with my friends Benny and Jason and their mom and her boyfriend. I lived in their basement for nine months while I finished high school. It was a blue-collar household. Their mom made eight dollars an hour working for a Catholic charity, but she cooked good meals from cheap ingredients and didn&rsquo;t ask me for rent. I gave her money sometimes. Benny and Jay eventually went into the heating-and-air business, and their sister Chrissy joined the pipe-fitters union. One thing I&rsquo;ve known for a long time is that poor people are much more likely to give you a place to stay than rich people are.</p>

<p>After Chuck Berry was done playing, he sat on a table and signed autographs for the union guys. Then he fell off the table.</p>

<h5><u><em>January 20</em></u></h5>

<p>It&rsquo;s the day after the caucus. The convention center where everyone filed their stories last night was nothing but cables and wires by eight o&rsquo;clock this morning. The only journalists left are the ones who missed their flights. The hotel lobbies are empty, and the campaign offices are stripped of anything that can be sold for more than a dollar. Everything&rsquo;s been stuffed into boxes, wrapped in tape, and shipped overnight to New Hampshire. The only people in line at the coffee shop are the governor of Iowa and a reporter from the <em>Des Moines Register</em>.</p>

<p>I thought I would hang out and try to relax, but I&rsquo;m already feeling the itch to go east. Maybe I should go home to San Francisco for a day or two. I miss my girlfriend, but she wouldn&rsquo;t want to see me the way I am now, a depraved and obsessed political animal. Or maybe she would. She likes it when I cry.</p>

<p>I woke up this morning wound tight as a drum and stone sober, a map of Iowa lit like a computer screen across the back of my mind. There was a moment between sleep and waking when it was still January 19 and I could see every precinct and knew every delegate&rsquo;s name and was in every caucus in the state. It was like watching a house burn.</p>

<p>Iowa voters picked Kerry and Edwards, surprising everybody, and embarrassing me in particular. Really, I shouldn&rsquo;t be surprised. My political predictions are always wrong. Smart people don&rsquo;t make predictions, but I&rsquo;m a gambler. I don&rsquo;t see any reason to change.</p>

<p>The youth vote stayed home, as everybody said they would. Meanwhile, both of last night&rsquo;s winners voted for the resolution authorizing force in Iraq, both voted for the <span class="smallcaps">Patriot</span> Act, and neither wants to kill the Bush tax cut; they just want to make it more fair, which is nice of them, considering how wealthy they are.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong class="large">A</strong> caucus doesn&rsquo;t make sense until you see it. Each precinct is awarded a certain number of delegates. To get a delegate, a candidate has to win 15 percent of the room, rounding up. At the caucus I observed, there were forty-nine caucusgoers. Fifteen percent was 7.2, so you needed eight votes to get a delegate. There were officially four delegates, but if six candidates had received 15 percent, there would have been six delegates. If &ldquo;undecided&rdquo; gets 15 percent, there&rsquo;s an undecided delegate. In 1976 Jimmy Carter did not win Iowa; undecided won Iowa.</p>

<p>The crazy thing is that, although it takes just 15 percent to get one delegate, it takes 50 percent to get two delegates. In Precinct 43, where I was, the three Kucinich supporters threw their votes to Edwards, pushing him over 50 percent.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Why are the Kucinich supporters going for Edwards?&rdquo; I asked Josh.</p>

<p>&ldquo;The deal is done,&rdquo; he said enigmatically, crossing his arms and nodding his head.</p>

<p>This morning my mind was still on the Kucinich-Edwards deal. I called Kucinich&rsquo;s headquarters from my cellphone. An aide answered the phone. &ldquo;What I&rsquo;m about to say is completely ridiculous,&rdquo; I told him. &ldquo;You&rsquo;re going to laugh. But I heard you put the word out to your caucusgoers that if they were not viable, they were supposed to join John Edwards.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Well,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;it&rsquo;s both simple and complicated.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yeah?&rdquo; I said.</p>

<p>&ldquo;You know you need 15 percent to be viable?&rdquo;</p>

<p>I let him keep going.</p>

<p>&ldquo;We made a deal with the Edwards people that if they weren&rsquo;t viable, they would join us, and if we weren&rsquo;t viable, we would join them.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I stopped on the cold street. It was warmer than it&rsquo;s been for the last few days, but you could still get frostbite if you talked too long on a cellphone without gloves. I asked the Kucinich aide to repeat what he had just said, and he did, word for word. He waited for me to ask him another question, but I didn&rsquo;t have any more questions. It hurt.</p>

<p>Have you ever had one of those moments when your self-image completely changes? I thought I had grown cynical and bitter, but this morning I suddenly realized I was idealistic and naive.</p>

<p>Edwards, who was viable in just about every caucus in the state, made a deal with Kucinich, who was viable in almost no caucuses, to trade unviable caucusgoers. Kucinich had plenty of unviable caucusgoers, and Edwards had very few. Edwards got the farm; Kucinich got nothing. All the time Kucinich spent in Iowa, he was basically working for Edwards. Ideologically, it would have made more sense for Kucinich to partner with the Dean camp, but Kucinich had decided to play politics.</p>

<p>After all the candidates&rsquo; parties last night, I went to Lucky&rsquo;s Pub, which is located between the Dean office and the Edwards office. &ldquo;There are no Republicans in this bar,&rdquo; one of the Dean workers said. They raised their glasses and put their arms around each other. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s all Democrats here.&rdquo; Then they started to chant, &ldquo;No more Bush! No more Bush!&rdquo; Across the room, the Edwards camp began to chant, &ldquo;Go, Edwards, Go! Go, Edwards, Go!&rdquo; and the Dean supporters were quickly drowned out.</p>

<h5><em><u>January 22</u><br />
New Hampshire</em></h5>

<p>The entire Iowa circus has transplanted itself here to New Hampshire. There are camera crews roaming the halls of the Manchester EconoLodge. Two miles away, across the river, is the Holiday Inn, where all the action is, but the few rooms left there are going for two hundred dollars a night, and that&rsquo;s too much to pay to stay anywhere in New Hampshire.</p>

<p>The rooms at the EconoLodge are large and have a fridge and a microwave. They&rsquo;re meant for living by the week, and maybe the weeks will become months, and maybe the months will become years, until one day you get caught doing something you shouldn&rsquo;t, or you get on a bus and go far away. The thing I like about hotels is that you never have to make a commitment, and you never have to say goodbye.</p>

<p>Everyone is still talking about Dean&rsquo;s over-the-top caucus-night victory speech in Des Moines. (Though 18 percent was an undeniable defeat, Dean declared the results a victory; all the candidates except Gephardt declared victory.) The press is calling it a public meltdown. But I was at that event with Josh. None of the reporters who saw Dean&rsquo;s speech stuck around to file a blistering expos&eacute; on his caucus-night crackup. They saw a candidate addressing thousands of disappointed campaign workers, who responded well to Dean&rsquo;s &ldquo;Yeeeahhh!&rdquo; But the reporters in Washington, D.C., and New York City, who watched the speech on <span class="smallcaps">TV</span>, saw something else.</p>

<p>&ldquo;How about that yell?&rdquo; they said.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Strong stuff.&rdquo;</p>

<p>In the morning Dean&rsquo;s &ldquo;Yeeeahhh!&rdquo; was all over television and radio.</p>

<p>The night before, though, the reporters didn&rsquo;t even stick around after the speech. They were eager to get to the winner&rsquo;s party at the Fort Des Moines, where the liquor was top-shelf and free, and the appetizers came with toothpicks. An hour after the biggest story of the week, the press area was empty, nothing but thirty phone lines hanging from a corkboard ceiling. By 11 <span class="smallcaps">P.M.</span> the filing center was deserted, and it was just supporters drinking beer, saying goodbye, and making out.</p>

<p>When Dean spoke on caucus night, he was talking to the kids in the orange hats who had been knocking on doors all weekend, the Perfect Storm. They had come from everywhere, but their presence had hurt more than it had helped. People in Iowa didn&rsquo;t like to see unshaven kids at their door holding clipboards.</p>

<p>The Kerry office did things differently: a handful of veterans on the phone, a target for each district, a war room lit with lights. When a precinct became viable, a blue light went on, and the word went out to shift efforts to the next precinct. Very organized, very slick. No dirty hippies in orange hats.</p>

<p>The word on the street now is that Dean is finished. Gephardt&rsquo;s Teamsters are wheels-up across the northeast. Kerry and Edwards are very much in it, though everybody thinks Edwards is running for vice president. Josh and I have our room at the EconoLodge, and last night at 2 <span class="smallcaps">a.m.</span> we snuck up to the seventh floor of the Holiday Inn and charged sixty dollars&rsquo; worth of wireless Internet to a major television network&rsquo;s tab. This is outsider journalism, guerrilla style.</p>

<h5><u><em>January 25</em></u></h5>

<p>Iowa was on fire, but only in Des Moines. In New Hampshire, primary mania is statewide. You&rsquo;re never more than forty minutes from a rally or a chili feed.</p>

<p>It&rsquo;s hard to watch Dean right now, because I liked him more when he was rattling off the states he was going to win and then shouting, &ldquo;Yeeeahhh!&rdquo; to an enthusiastic crowd. But that&rsquo;s just me. I&rsquo;ve never voted for a winner.</p>

<p>Still, I love politics. I would sleep in a hallway to hear Wesley Clark connect unemployment to family values, or to hear John Edwards say he&rsquo;s going to &ldquo;cut the lobbyists off at the knees.&rdquo; At a Democratic dinner in Nashua, Kucinich unveiled his new rap song: &ldquo;I&rsquo;m a patriot / Can&rsquo;t you see? / I can&rsquo;t believe / you&rsquo;d name a missile after me.&rdquo; By the end I was so high on political juice that my own problems had melted away.</p>

<p>Josh and I have discovered that fringe candidates John Buchanan and Dick Bosa are sharing a smoke-filled room three doors down from ours in the EconoLodge. I was surprised to see them together. They&rsquo;re both still running, but Dick is also working as John&rsquo;s campaign manager. The room looked as if two junkies lived there. Dick said he doesn&rsquo;t want to run after New Hampshire, except maybe in Texas. John writes online articles about himself under the pseudonym Omar Suarez, which is the name of the character in <em>Scarface </em>who gets pushed from a helicopter with a rope around his neck.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong class="large">A</strong>n Edwards rally resembles a college football game. There are hundreds of people who can&rsquo;t get into the room. There&rsquo;ll be three times that many or more, however, when Kerry shows up just down the road two hours from now. I took some informal polls and found that 80 percent of the people at an Edwards rally are undecided, whereas 80 percent at a Dean or Kerry rally are voting for the candidate they came to see.</p>

<p>Edwards is so sincere you would never know that he&rsquo;s delivered the same speech five times a day for months. Kerry&rsquo;s events are still painful for me, but he&rsquo;s gotten better. Dean is still softening his tone and wearing sweaters. I asked Kucinich about trading unviables with John Edwards in Iowa. He shrugged and said he wanted delegates.</p>

<p>At a Democratic dinner, Dean used most of his seven minutes to thank half the people in the room. He was responding to criticism that he hadn&rsquo;t thanked the Iowans before he left the state. I love hearing a speech and knowing where it came from. Following the ins and outs of a campaign is like taking the jittery pulse of a country with an unelected president in a time of war.</p>

<p>Politics is about holding people accountable for their record, but it&rsquo;s also about listening to what they say, and separating the politics from the person. You never get it until you&rsquo;re on the inside, and even then you don&rsquo;t get it. But there are days when the roar is so quiet and clean it&rsquo;s like being inside a wave.</p>

<p class="ckeditor-shortcode"><figure class="photo photo-outset-center-medium">
	<div>
					<div>
				<img src="data:image/svg+xml;charset=utf-8,%3Csvg xmlns%3D'http%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2F2000%2Fsvg' viewBox%3D'0 0 1960 1230'%2F%3E"
		data-src=https://226391-691236-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/thumbs/980x615r/photos/1510020000_345-21-emory.jpg data-src-retina=https://226391-691236-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/thumbs/1960x1230r/photos/1510020000_345-21-emory.jpg
	 alt="345 - Emory 2 - Elliott"
	 class="lazy">

									<figcaption>
																											<div class="photo-credit">
																			© <a href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/contributors/bill-emory">
